<https://n2t.net/ark:/27023/d4474375e7aeafa5a104f50cbf3bcffe> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#name> "KALKHOUDER GEMAAKT VAN EEN KALEBAS, MET EEN KALKSPATEL VAN HOUT" .
<https://n2t.net/ark:/27023/d4474375e7aeafa5a104f50cbf3bcffe> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "Beschrijvingskaart: Maart 1948 :\r\nEen langgerekte kalebas van een oranje-gele kleur ; in het middengedeelte zijn met schuine lijntjes verschillende figuren gesneden o. a. visgraten. Deze lijnfiguren zijn aangebracht in driehoeken, afwisselend met de punt naar boven en naar beneden gericht ; de groefjes zijn met kalk aangezet, terwijl de ondergrond een bruinachtige tint heeft, vermoedelijk verkregen door branden. Onder dit middengedeelte zijn nog vijf vrij grillige ornamenten aagebracht, die misschien vogels uitbeelden.\r\nDe houten stop heeft een lange steel, die ver in de koker gaat, boven de kalebas is hij gevormdt tot een mensenromp met de armen langs het lichaam, het hoofd heeft een zeer spitse kin ; ogen, neus en oren zijn duidelijk en realistisch aagegeven.\r\n\r\n\r\nMost of the lime containers were made from the lagenaria gourd, of two groups can be distinguished: one with a cucumber shape reserved for the men  (like this object) and another with a pear-shape configuration that was reserved for women. \r\nMany gourds bear a pokerwork decoration. The figures were burnt into the rind with the glowing end of a sharpened rib of sago-palm leaf, which was blown in continuously to keep it burning. This technique explains why the resulting lines were occasionally rather irregular. Skilled experts were called on when a nicely ornamented gourd was wanted.\r\nOne of the leading motifs in the decorative pattern is the spiral, which occurs in two versions, single and double.\r\nAlmost all artefacts in the Sentani region were adorned with engravings, paintings or burned with figurative and geometrical designs, often interlocking spiral ornaments (referred to as fouw). These decorations are labelled as homo, a term that can be translated as ‘’writing’’ and refers both to sculpting and painting.  In addition to aesthetically enhancing artefacts, homo give information about the person, family, and village who owned the object. Specific designs were used by particular groups of people and passed on from one generation to another. Each family or clan had its own designs that were kept. In addition, political alliances between villages were visualised by the use of specific designs. Designs and ornaments have mythological origins. This is suggested by local narratives in which decorations often figure in relation to spirits and  ancestors. The clans used to hold control over  the reproduction of the animal’s images.\r\nLime containers were among the possessions of nearly every man and woman. Most followed the custom of chewing lime and betel nut as a kind of stimulant.\r\nPlastic cups or empty beer cans replaced the former materials.\r\nAll lime gourd were provided with a spatula. These instruments vary in shape from simple undecorated stick to objects with elaborately carved handle, occasionally in a shape of a human figure. The latter were restricted in use to the elders, heads of clans and their families and wives. They may have their own individual name." .
